{{combin-stub}}

In [[set theory]],  '''Jensen's covering theorem''' states  that if [[zero sharp|0<sup>#</sup>]] does not exist then every uncountable set of ordinals is contained in a constructible set of the same cardinality. Informally this conclusion says that the [[constructible universe]] is close to the  universe of all sets. The first proof  appeared in {{harv|Devlin|Jensen|1975}}. [[Jack Silver|Silver]] later gave a fine structure free proof using his [[Silver machine|machines]] and finally  {{harvs|txt|authorlink=Menachem Magidor|last=Magidor|year=1990}} gave an even simpler proof.

The converse of Jensen's covering theorem is also true: if 0<sup>#</sup> exists then the countable set of all cardinals less than ℵ<sub>ω</sub> cannot be covered by a constructible set of cardinality less than ℵ<sub>ω</sub>.

In his book ''Proper Forcing'', [[Saharon Shelah|Shelah]] proved a strong form of Jensen's covering lemma.

